paper.name: Premise Order Matters
paper.prompt:
Create a flowchart diagram showing how premise ordering affects reasoning performance.

Include these key elements:
- Multiple premise arrangements: Different orderings of the same premises
- Processing flow: How models handle different orderings
- Performance impact: Show accuracy variations based on order
- Optimal ordering: Demonstrate which orders work best
- Position bias: Highlight how early/late premises affect reasoning

Use a branching diagram showing multiple premise order paths. Color code by performance (green=good, red=poor).

diagrams.code:
direction right
// Premise Ordering Effects on Reasoning Performance
title Premise Ordering Effects on Reasoning Performance

// Groups and nodes
Start [shape: oval, color: lightblue]
Premise Arrangements [color: lightyellow] {
  Original Ordering
  Reversed Ordering
  Random Ordering
}
Model Processing [color: lightgray] {
  Process Original Ordering
  Process Reversed Ordering
  Process Random Ordering
}
Performance Results [color: lightgray] {
  Accuracy Original [color: green]
  Accuracy Reversed [color: red]
  Accuracy Random [color: red]
  Optimal Ordering Identified [shape: diamond, color: lightgreen]
}
Position Bias [color: lightgray] {
  Evaluate Early Premise Impact
  Evaluate Late Premise Impact
}
End [shape: oval, color: lightgreen]

// Relationships
Start > Premise Arrangements

Original Ordering > Process Original Ordering
Reversed Ordering > Process Reversed Ordering
Random Ordering > Process Random Ordering

Process Original Ordering > Accuracy Original
Process Reversed Ordering > Accuracy Reversed
Process Random Ordering > Accuracy Random

Accuracy Original > Optimal Ordering Identified: [color: green]
Accuracy Reversed > Optimal Ordering Identified: [color: red]
Accuracy Random > Optimal Ordering Identified: [color: red]
Optimal Ordering Identified > Position Bias
Position Bias > End
